rvivor's guilt, but also with the lingering antisemitism and anti-Jewish violence in Poland even after the war ended. Harrowing, moving, and deeply insightful, Rabbi Thorne's firsthand account offers a rediscovered perspective on the twentieth century's greatest tragedy.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aMagilow, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aSinger, Isaac Bashevis.1 aThorne, Emanuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019z978311065352640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978801684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978801684.jpg  a978-3-11-065352-6  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG